default1. defaultBackgrounddefault&#xa0;
default1.1.
default 
defaultMyalgic Encephalomyelitis (M.E.) is a fluctuating 
defaultlong-term condition 
defaultthat 
defaultaffects around 250,000 men, women and children in the UK.
default 
defaultIt causes symptoms affecting many body systems, more commonly the nervous and immune systems. 
defaultAround 25% of patients are severely affected, and may be confined to bed or unable to leave the house without the use of a wheelchair. 
default&#xa0;
default1.2
default. Action for M.E. is the UK’s largest charity for people affected by M.E.
default 
defaultWe provide information and support, campaign for better services and more effective treatments
default, 
defaultand drive and invest in research.
default&#xa0;
default1.
default3
default. Our
default submission 
defaultfocuses on four terms of reference from the Health Select Committee’s inquiry into the management of long-term conditions.
defaultinquiry into the Management of long-term conditions inquiry into the Management of long-term conditions
default It is 
defaultbased on responses to a 14-question survey for people with M.E. in England, devised by Action for M.E. and publicised via our Online M.E. Centre
default and social media sites
default from 4 to 30 April 2013.
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default. 
defaultThe survey was answered by 
default252 
defaultpeople with M.E. 
defaultThis was a good response given the short time frame. Results of the survey reflect what we expected and 
